This is a PUBLIC ANNOUNCEMENT which will hopefully help out a lot of sysops 
in the scene who run an Ami-Express BBS to decide which cause of action is
most appropriate to their circumstance. I.e; choose to pay and upgrade to 
Version 4.00 or look for an alternative system sporting similar features,
'look' and 'feel'. Until today the only viable scene alternative was to
turn to 'S-Express' since 'C-Net' has always been very scene-unfriendly,
being more suited to P.D and business systems. We have now decided to come
out of the closet and leak some information pertaning to the inniment 
release of "Swift-Professional"...

This release comes after the announcement of the very expensive 'upgrade' 
fee`s which are being touted for the move over to Ami-Express Revision 4,
we feel the upgrade prices for registered users is far to high for the
average sysop and hence we now present our answer to your problems...








                      Introducing Swift Professional
                    ¯ ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯ ¯



This announcement was originally to be delayed until September 1994 after 
which we felt the research, development and testing phases would be 
sufficiently completed for the initial release of Swift-Professional ®.
After the late news of the massive price upgrades for /X4.xx we are now 
releasing theses vital notes for sysops before they part with their
hard earned cash... The /X market monopoly situation is history!

Swift-Professional ® is a brand new BBS System written exclusively for the 
Amiga scene by Amiga coding enthusiasts. Key members of the Amiga community
have given many interesting and worthy suggestions, many of which have been 
greatly recieved. Swift has been in constant development for over a year and
thousands of revisions to the source have taken place since its initial beta
stages.

Sysops currently running Ami-Express (3 series) will be pleased to know that 
this system is based around the concepts of this BBS System and so they will
feel right at home using Swift. Infact Swift is 99% compatible with most
doors written for Ami-Express v3.xx .People after reading this statement may 
feel that Swift is therefore a blatent rip-off of the PD Ami-Express source-
code released about a year ago. We must STRESS that this is not the case. 

Swift is loosely based around the original source to Ami-Express v3.xx. It
has undergone an almost complete re-write. Also during this re-code we opted
to program the new system using highly efficient optimised Motorola MC680x0
Assembly language. Opting for assembly language has had its disadvantage for
us in that development has taken far longer than would have been the case
in using a high-level language like SAS/C. The overwheming benefits that
development in assembly has had to the system are that object-code is very
very compact (it is now half the size of the current Express incarnations)
and from memory conservation aspects you can expect to run a 4 or maybe 
even 5 node BBS on a standard Amiga-A1200 and still have some free memory!
The speed increase is also quite substantial, you can expect to see text-
output on an `020 race to about 3 times faster than /X can handle when 
running flat out on an 030...







                     Swift as a System for Door Writers
                   ¯ ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯ ¯


Below explains information for door developers, coders and just the 
inquisitive. Non-technical knowledgable sysops may skip this section...

Fundemental changes have taken place to the original single node type design
of the original code. Ami-Express was written by Thomas X quite a few years
ago when BBS`s where tame single node systems run of 20mb hard-disks... Now
the number of nodes a BBS uses can run into double figures and a thousand
or more members with 3-Gigs online is not uncommon.

The old port interface was far too inflexible and provided far too many 
limitations for a fast well designed system which we intended Swift to be.
Swift has been written with a different approach. Instead of having one 
main program which sets up links for each node and for each door we have 
developed a new system to minimise CPU overhead and memory usage. 
It utilizes many amiga specific features;


		BBS:Swift			- node callback code,
						  kickstarts the nodes

		LIBS:Swift.library		- main amiga shared library
						  access for doors and each
						  node shares the same code

		L:Swift-handler			- for CLI Door access, 
						  re-directs pr_CLI, pr_COS
	                                          input and ouput to swift
						  without any speed loss
						  or time usage overheads...


Door writers will be pleased to hear they can develop their doors and access
ALL important memory structures, variables and routines virtually DIRECT via
the mult-access shared library. Many examples will be supplied with the 
release and Assembly programmers documentation/examples will not be left out!

You now no longer need to setup inflexible, memory hungry door ports. Simple
calls to the 'swift.library' allow writers very easy development and faster
development & debugging times. You can ofcourse still develop doors using the
old system as its fully compatible with the Ami-Express 32-Node Multi-Comm
structure and JH-Door interface but the new interface allow far more 
flexiblity. You now specify the node to access as a parameter for each library
call enabling you to access all active nodes without ANY door interface 
polling! - Its all handled via the library.. Extensive documentation will
be included and many examples will be supplied...





          Swift Professional - Current *NEW* [BUILT-IN] Features
         ¯ ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯ ¯

Below contains some of the new additional features over the current
Ami-Express 3.xx series that Swift has (and over the planned /X4.0 
release! - grin)


»	Swift is Fully "Localized" so that every single BBS String is 
	configurable. Catalogues will be available to support different
	languages. This means each user can select their language preference
	(catalogue availability permitting) thus enabling multi-language 
	support for each individual member of your BBS. A catalogue editor 
	will be supplied so you can translate and create your own custom 
	catalogues and really change the 'look' and 'feel' of your system!

»	Swifts internal commands, like 'g' for goodbye, 'd' download, etc.
	are fully configurable and all names are redefinable, etc. Please
	refer to the example configuration script for more information
	about commands...

»	Swift supports ALL CLI-driven doors making available online games 
	like 'Hack-and-Slash' using our custom written handler...

»	Swift supports the Public-Domain specifications for BI-DIRECTIONAL 
	'Hydra' file-transfers enabling chat, upload and download facilities 
	with modems supporting full-duplex transfers and the appropriate
	terminal software.

»	Swift currently consumes only 250k per node, (this may vary in
	the final release) but our general aim is to reduce this amount to
	even less during later stages of development!

»	Swift can be configured to support upto 100 independent nodes
	in a true multi-tasking fasion...
	
»	Swift has a brand new Workbench 2.x+ style guidelines complient
	GUI interface.

»	Swift can be configured using a brand new GUI control interface
	or more seasoned sysops can configure the BBS directly via the
	configuration bbs script. Sysops can carry out Configurations 
	while on-line. (see supplied files for a beta example of a bbs
	configuration script)

»	Swift Sysop node snooping screens are now far more flexible;

	> Use of custom palettes		 - Palette Requesrs
	> Use of custom fonts			 - Font Requesters
	> Use of Screenmodes including AGA modes - Screenmode Requesters
	> Use of Public screens for consoles
	> Border blanking available on OS3.x+
	> Optional Scrollback buffers on nodes

»	Swift has a Special cutdown size versions of callerslogs,
	udlogs, etc. in a very compact format taking much less storage..

»	Swift has a built in fully featured, fully configurable
	File nuker! This has a public-file nuke facility so that users
	can delete files they uploaded if they discover they have uploaded
	a fake .. will reduce (co)sysop maintenance overheads...

»	Swift has Public "EALLS" mailing facilities. Users can send "PUBLIC
	EALLS"  that everyone has the ability to recieve however each user 
	can set their public eall access level so they recieve public ealls
	only from access levels they set, etc. eg; 200+.

»	Swift has Public and private mail-screening facilities, users can
	block mail from certain users and or access levels (not sysops)

»	Swift mail sent Private to the "local-sysop" cannot be read by anyone
	else, not even co-sysops! (optional)

»	Swift has some new "stealth file-transfer" options;

	> User-2-User Encrypted File/Mail-Transfers 
	  - Whereby only 1 particular user can DL the file...

	> Password Encrypted File/Mail-Transfers
	  - Anyone with decryption password, useful for group confidential
	    materials, information, source-codes, demos & releases, etc.)

	> Optional automatic usage of PGP and Keyrings to validate releases
	  and pass one encrypt mail...

»	Swifts accounting system is fully encrypted, not just the user
	passwords. Non-reversible algorithms for passwords and special
	BBS 'Seed' cyphier strings will be required to alter/access any
	user-data information from outside the door-interface making
	BBS Viruses which add Sysop access accounts a thing of the past!
	Actual user.data type file is locked out from access during BBS 
	usage thereby preventing even reading or writing to the files...

»	Swift has a new command to let users view the portion of "CallersLog" 
	Relating to themselves. This allows them to view if someone has been
	using their account.. View their last 10 downloads/uploads etc. 
	They`ll ONLY be able to view THEIR OWN CALLS!

»	Users have a brand new preferences section to customise their BBS
	usage to their preferences. This allows them to customise the way
	they logon to the BBS, etc.

